Problem Description:
# Furious Stones (Optional)
Mr. Garlic has $n$ furious stones in his warehouse, each with two attributes: anger and irritability. Carrying these furious stones will grant corresponding attributes, specifically: the total anger value is the product of the anger values of all furious stones, and the total irritability value is the sum of the irritability values of all furious stones. Now Mr. Garlic wants to know how to select furious stones (cannot choose none) to minimize the difference between the total anger value and the total irritability value. Please help him calculate this minimum difference.

### Input format

The first line is an integer $n\ (1\le n \le 10)$.

The following $n$ lines, each with two integers separated by a space, represent the anger and irritability values of a furious stone.

The data guarantees that the product of all anger values and the sum of all irritability values are within the `int` range.

### Output format

An integer, representing the minimum difference between the total anger value and the total irritability value.

Your program should use file input and output. Read the input from a file named 'stone.in' and write the output to a file named 'stone.out'.

### Time Limit
2000ms

### Memory Limit
262144KB

This is an incorrect code to the problem:
```c++
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
int n,a[1000001],b[1000001],minn=1e9;
void dfs(int x,int sum1,int sum2) {
    if(x==n){
        minn=min(abs(sum1-sum2),minn);
        return ;
    }
    dfs(x+1,sum1*a[x],sum2+b[x]);
    dfs(x+1,sum1,sum2);
}
int main() {
    freopen("stone.in", "r", stdin);
    freopen("stone.out", "w", stdout);
    cin>>n;
