Problem Description:
# Gem Collector II (Optional)

Mr. Garlic has recently become obsessed with all kinds of shiny gems and has become a new gem collector. Mr. Garlic has arranged all his gems in a long corridor, starting from number $1$.

Every time Mr. Garlic goes to the gem market, he buys several identical gems and puts them at the end of his collection.

Now some friends want to visit Mr. Garlic's collection. In order to show off his wealth, Mr. Garlic wants to rearrange his gems.

Sorting rules:

  1. Gems of different types with higher average unit prices are prioritized, and if equal, those with smaller purchase dates are prioritized;
  2. Gems of the same type with higher purchase prices are prioritized;
  3. Gems of the same type and price with smaller purchase dates are prioritized.

Mr. Garlic wants to find the sum of the absolute values of the differences in all gem numbers changes. Can you help him calculate it?

Note: Absolute value of the difference in gem number changes. For example, if a gem has a number $3$ before sorting and $5$ after sorting, the absolute value of the difference is $2$. If a gem has a number $5$ before sorting and $1$ after sorting, the absolute value of the difference is $4$.

### Input format

The first line contains a positive integer $n\ (1 \leq n \leq 10^5)$, representing the number of times Mr. Garlic buys gems;

The next $n$ lines each contain three integers $r$, $p$, and $k$, representing the type of gem, the purchase unit price, and the quantity purchased (gems of the same type but different prices will appear).

$1 \leq r,\ p \leq 10^3$, $\sum k \leq 10^6$, and the total number of gems Mr. Garlic buys is less than or equal to $10^6$.

