Problem Description:
# Mr. Garlic's Study Room IIII

Mr. Garlic has $n$ bookshelves in his study room, numbered consecutively as $1,2,3,\ldots,n$. However, having only bookshelves seems not cultured enough, so he bought $m$ books. Mr. Garlic has devised a plan to place the $i$-th book on the $k_i$-th bookshelf. Now, please output which books will be on each bookshelf after implementing the plan.

### Input Format

The first line has two integers $n\ (1<n \le 10^4)$ and $m\ ( 1 < m \le 10^5)$, representing the number of bookshelves and the number of books, respectively.

The following $m$ lines each have an integer $k_i (1\le k_i \le n)$ indicating that the $i$-th book should be placed on the $k_i$-th bookshelf, and a string $s_i$ (length no more than $20$) representing the name of the book.

### Output Format

Output a total of $n$ lines.

Each line starts with two integers $id$ and $cnt$, representing the bookshelf's number and the total number of books on that shelf, followed by $cnt$ book titles (sorted in lexicographic order), separated by a space.

### Time Limit
1000ms

### Memory Limit
131072KB

This is an incorrect code to the problem:
```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
using namespace std;
int main () {
    vector<int> v[10005];
    int id;
    string name;
    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        for(int j = 0; j < m; j++){
            cin >> id >> name;
            v[id].push_back(name);
        }
    }
    for(int i = 0; i < v.size(); i++){
        cout << id << v.size();
        sort(v.begin(), v.end());
        cout << v[i];
    }
    return 0;
}
```
### Response:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
using namespace std;
int main () {
    vector<string> v[100005];
    int id;
    string name;
    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
            cin >> id >> name;
            v[id].push_back(name);
    }
    for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++){
        cout << i << " " << v[i].size();
        sort(v[i].begin(), v[i].end());
        for(int j = 0; j < v[i].size(); j++){
            cout << " " << v[i][j];
        }
        cout << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

