###Instruction:
Problem Description:
# Maze

Given an $m \times n$ maze, there are two positions in the maze. Mr. Garlic wants to walk from one position to another. Of course, some places in the maze are open spaces, which Mr. Garlic can pass through, while others are obstacles that he must bypass. From one position in the maze, he can only walk to one of the $4$ adjacent positions. Of course, during the walking process, Mr. Garlic cannot walk outside the maze. What's troubling is that Mr. Garlic is not very good with directions. Therefore, he cannot make too many turns during the walking process, otherwise he will faint. We assume that the given two positions are both open spaces. At the beginning, the direction Mr. Garlic is facing is not determined. He can choose any of the $4$ directions to start without counting as a turn. Can Mr. Garlic walk from one position to another?

### Input format

The first line is an integer $t$ ($1 \le t \le 100$), indicating the number of test data sets, followed by $t$ groups of test data.

For each test data set, the first line contains two integers $m, n (1 \le m, n \le 100)$, indicating the number of rows and columns in the maze, followed by $m$ lines, each containing $n$ characters. The character `'.'` indicates that the position is an open space, and the character `'*'` indicates that the position is an obstacle. There are only these two types of characters in the input data. The last line of each test data set contains $5$ integers $k, x_1, y_1, x_2, y_2$ ($1 \le k \le 10, 1 \le x_1, x_2 \le n$, $1 \le y_1, y_2 \le m$), where $k$ represents the maximum number of turns Mr. Garlic can make, $(x_1, y_1)$ and $(x_2, y_2)$ represent the two positions, with $x_1, x_2$ corresponding to columns and $y_1, y_2$ corresponding to rows.

### Output format

Each test data set corresponds to one line. If Mr. Garlic can walk from one position to another, output `"yes"`; otherwise, output `"no"`.

Your program should use file input and output. Read the input from a file named 'maze.in' and write the output to a file named 'maze.out'.

