# Perfect Match (Optional)
Recently, Mr. Garlic has been dedicated to studying the pairing problems of his classmates (don't overthink it, just dance partners). Through various reasoning and experiments, he has gained a lot of practical experience. For example, according to his observation, people with similar heights seem to get along better.

As Halloween approaches, Mr. Garlic plans to organize a large-scale "Perfect Match" pairing event at the school. For the participants of this event, Mr. Garlic has his unique selection method. He hopes to choose an equal number of men and women with very close heights. This selection method is easy to implement. He asks everyone in the school to line up according to their height, and then selects a continuous group of people from the line, ensuring that the number of men and women is equal. To make the event more lively, Mr. Garlic naturally hopes to choose as many people as possible. Please write a program to tell him the maximum number of people he can select.

### Input Format

The first line has a positive integer $n\ (1\le n \le 10^5)$, representing the number of people in the school.

The second line has $n$ numbers separated by spaces, these numbers can only be $0$ or $1$, where $0$ represents a female student and $1$ represents a male student.

### Output Format

Output a non-negative integer, which represents the length of the longest continuous subsequence with an equal number of men and women in the input data.

Your program should use file input and output. Read the input from a file named 'pair.in' and write the output to a file named 'pair.out'.

### Time Limit
1000ms

### Memory Limit
